# Approval Protocol — {{team_name}}

> When + how the team requests human approval. The contract every
> `semi`/`supervised` agent honors before any L3+ tool call.

## When approval is required

Per agent autonomy + tool blast level (see `blast-radius.md`):

| Autonomy | L1 | L2 | L3 | L4 |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `full` | proceed | proceed | proceed | proceed |
| `semi` | proceed | proceed | proceed | **approval required** |
| `supervised` | proceed | proceed | **approval required** | **approval required** |

Approval is NOT required for L1 (read-only) or L2 (write-scoped to own
or designated sibling state) regardless of autonomy.

## Approval channel

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Medium | Telegram |
| Thread | `approval_thread_id` (per `runtime/reference-impl/.env.example`) |
| Bot user | the team's bot, configured at `.env` `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` |
| Authorized approvers | per `.env` `TELEGRAM_AUTHORIZED_USERS` (comma-separated user IDs) |

Approval messages live in a DIFFERENT Telegram thread from briefings
and from escalations. Rationale: approvals are time-sensitive
decisions that must not be buried.

## Request message format

```
[APPROVE/DENY] {{agent_id}}
Correlation: {{correlation_id}}
Action: {{tool_name}}({{args_summary_redacted}})
Reversibility: {{reversibility_tag}}
Reasoning: {{tool_reasoning}}

Reply: /approve {{correlation_id}}
   OR  /deny    {{correlation_id}}
```

| Field | Source | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `agent_id` | env `CLAUDE_AGENT_ID` | Set by `wake.sh` |
| `correlation_id` | env `CLAUDE_CORRELATION_ID` | Flows through entire wake |
| `tool_name` | runtime hook | The MCP tool about to fire |
| `args_summary_redacted` | hook | PII-redacted single-line summary |
| `reversibility_tag` | derived from blast | `reversible` / `hard-to-reverse` / `irreversible` |
| `tool_reasoning` | env `TOOL_REASONING` | 1-2 sentence rationale set by agent before invoking |

`semi`/`supervised` agents that fail to set `TOOL_REASONING` have the
tool BLOCKED with `result: blocked, reason: missing-tool-reasoning`.

## Approval response

The operator replies in the approval thread:

| Reply | Effect |
|---|---|
| `/approve <correlation-id>` | Append to `approvals.jsonl` with `decision: approve`; agent unblocks |
| `/approve <correlation-id> <reasoning>` | Same + reasoning captured |
| `/deny <correlation-id>` | Append with `decision: deny`; agent skips action |
| `/deny <correlation-id> <reasoning>` | Same + reasoning captured |

The `<correlation-id>` arg disambiguates concurrent pending approvals.
Multiple agents may have pending approvals simultaneously.

## Timeout behavior

If no approval lands within `{{approval_timeout_sec}}` seconds (default
600 = 10 minutes), the request escalates per
`../agents/<id>/escalation.md`:

- Tier 1 ping: re-send approval message tagged `[ESC1]`
- Tier 2 ping: re-send tagged `[ESC2]`
- Tier 3 final: escalate to `escalations_thread_id`; agent sets
  `last-run.json status: error`; subsequent wakes short-circuit

Each tier uses a derived child correlation-id (`<orig>-esc1`, etc.) to
bypass dedup in `telegram-send.sh`.

## Authorized users

Only Telegram user IDs in `.env` `TELEGRAM_AUTHORIZED_USERS` can
approve. Replies from other users are logged + ignored. Authorization
is enforced in `approval-router.sh` (or runtime equivalent), not by
Telegram itself.

For multi-approver setups (e.g., bank transfers > €X require two
approvers), extend the protocol: require two distinct authorized
approver IDs both posting `/approve <correlation-id>` within the
timeout window. Document the threshold per L4 tool.

## State persistence

```
.agentbloc/state/approvals.jsonl
```

Append-only. Two lines per round-trip:

1. `action: approval_request` — set when agent posts the message
2. `action: approval_response` — set when operator replies (or timeout)

Schema lives in `audit-trail.md`. `details.outcome` enum:
`approved` / `denied` / `timeout`.

## What "reversibility" means

The `reversibility_tag` in the request message helps the operator
decide quickly:

| Tag | Examples | Default response time |
|---|---|---|
| `reversible` | Send a draft email, create a calendar tentative | 30 min |
| `hard-to-reverse` | Send a customer email, create a calendar event with invitees | 5 min |
| `irreversible` | Bank transfer, payment, delete record | 1 min |

Phase 3 inventory protocol assigns reversibility per tool (in
`integrations/<tier>/<tool>` files). Operators triage by tag.

## Build-session responsibilities

1. Implement the request poster (Telegram MCP `sendMessage` to thread)
2. Implement the response listener (Telegram `getUpdates` long-poll)
3. Implement the timeout watchdog (re-pings + escalation tier ladder)
4. Implement the authorization check (sender ID matches authorized list)
5. Wire to PreToolUse hook so tool calls block until decision lands
6. Append to approvals.jsonl per `audit-trail.md` schema
7. Write tests (request fires; approve unblocks; deny blocks; timeout
   escalates; unauthorized reply ignored)

